1️⃣ What is the Singleton Design Pattern?

Definition

The Singleton Pattern ensures that:

A class has only one instance

Provides a global access point to that instance

Why do we need it?

Sometimes multiple instances of a class can cause problems.

Example:

Multiple database connection managers

Multiple logging systems

Multiple configuration managers

Instead, we want only one shared instance.

2️⃣ Basic Singleton Implementation

To implement the singleton pattern, a class must have three key elements: 
A private constructor to prevent direct instantiation of the class using the new keyword from outside the class.
A private static variable of the same class type that holds the single instance.
A public static method (commonly named getInstance()) that returns the single instance, creating it if it doesn't already exist. 

Core ideas:

Private constructor → prevent object creation outside

Static instance variable

Public static method to access instance

class Singleton {

    private static Singleton instance;

    private Singleton() {}

    public static Singleton getInstance() {
        if(instance == null) {
            instance = new Singleton();
        }
        return instance;
    }
}

Usage:

Singleton obj = Singleton.getInstance();

You cannot do this:

Singleton obj = new Singleton(); // ❌ constructor is private


3️⃣ Eager Initialization Singleton

In this approach, the object is created when the class is loaded.

class Singleton {

    private static final Singleton instance = new Singleton();

    private Singleton() {}

    public static Singleton getInstance() {
        return instance;
    }
}
How it works

JVM loads the class → object is created immediately.

Advantages

✔ Simple
✔ Thread-safe (class loading is thread-safe)

Disadvantages

❌ Object created even if never used

Example:

App starts
↓
Singleton object created
↓
But maybe never used

So memory is wasted.

4️⃣ Lazy Initialization Singleton

Object is created only when needed.

class Singleton {

    private static Singleton instance;

    private Singleton(){}

    public static Singleton getInstance() {
        if(instance == null) {
            instance = new Singleton();
        }
        return instance;
    }
}

--getInstance() is declared static, so it can be called without creating an object of the class.
--The first call to getInstance() creates the singleton object.
--Subsequent calls return the same instance, ensuring only one object exists.

Advantages

✔ Object created only when needed
✔ Saves memory

Problem

❌ Not thread-safe

5️⃣ Thread Safety Problem

Suppose two threads call getInstance() at the same time

Thread 1

if(instance == null) → true

Thread 2

if(instance == null) → true

Both create objects:

instance = new Singleton();
instance = new Singleton();

Now two instances exist ❌

Singleton is broken.

6️⃣ Thread Safe Singleton (Synchronized Method)
class Singleton {

    private static Singleton instance;

    private Singleton(){}

    public static synchronized Singleton getInstance() {

        if(instance == null) {
            instance = new Singleton();
        }

        return instance;
    }
}
How it works

synchronized ensures only one thread executes method at a time.

Problem

❌ Performance overhead
Every call requires lock.

7️⃣ Double Checked Locking (Best Classic Approach)

Improves performance.

class Singleton {

    private static volatile Singleton instance;

    private Singleton(){}

    public static Singleton getInstance() {

        if(instance == null) {

            synchronized(Singleton.class) {

                if(instance == null) {
                    instance = new Singleton();
                }

            }

        }

        return instance;
    }
}
Why volatile?

Prevents instruction reordering by JVM.

Without it, a partially constructed object may be returned.

8️⃣ Bill Pugh Singleton (Most Recommended)

Uses static inner class.

class Singleton {

    private Singleton(){}

    private static class SingletonHelper {
        private static final Singleton INSTANCE = new Singleton();
    }

    public static Singleton getInstance() {
        return SingletonHelper.INSTANCE;
    }
}
Why this is great

✔ Lazy initialization
✔ Thread safe
✔ No synchronization cost
✔ Clean code

This is often considered the best Java singleton implementation.

9️⃣ Enum Singleton (Safest in Java)

Joshua Bloch recommends this.

enum Singleton {

    INSTANCE;

    public void showMessage() {
        System.out.println("Hello Singleton");
    }
}

Usage

Singleton.INSTANCE.showMessage();
Advantages

✔ Thread-safe
✔ Prevents reflection attack
✔ Prevents serialization issues

🔟 Real Life Applications
1️⃣ Logger

Example:

LogManager.getLogger()

Single logging instance used across application.

2️⃣ Database Connection Manager

Instead of multiple connections:

DBConnectionManager.getInstance()

Used to manage connection pool.

3️⃣ Configuration Manager

Example:

AppConfig.getInstance()

Loads config file once and shares everywhere.

4️⃣ Cache Manager

Example:

CacheManager.getInstance()

Used in caching frameworks.

5️⃣ Spring Beans (Important for Interviews)

In Spring Framework, beans are Singleton by default.

Example:

@Service
class UserService {}

Spring creates one instance and shares it across application.

1️⃣1️⃣ Interview Follow-Up Questions

Interviewers often ask:

Q1

Why constructor must be private?

Answer:

To prevent object creation using new keyword.

Q2

How can Singleton be broken?

1️⃣ Reflection
2️⃣ Serialization
3️⃣ Cloning
4️⃣ Multithreading

Q3

Which Singleton implementation is best?

Best options:

1️⃣ Enum Singleton
2️⃣ Bill Pugh Singleton

